10308nam a22022455i 9781400842681DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008426817 a10.1515/97814008426812doi  a(DE-B1597)447107  a(OCoLC)979749950  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aQA42b.C57 2017 7aMAT0150002bisacsh04a510.1422300aCircles Disturbed :bThe Interplay of Mathematics and Narrative /ced. by Barry Mazur, Apostolos Doxiadis.  aCore Textbook 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (552 p.) :b91 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. From Voyagers to Martyrs -- tChapter 2. Structure of Crystal, Bucket of Dust -- tChapter 3. Deductive Narrative and the Epistemological Function of Belief in Mathematics -- tChapter 4. Hilbert on Theology and Its Discontents -- tChapter 5. Do Androids Prove Theorems in Their Sleep? -- tChapter 6. Visions, Dreams, and Mathematics -- tChapter 7. Vividness in Mathematics and Narrative -- tChapter 8. Mathematics and Narrative -- tChapter 9. Narrative and the Rationality of Mathematical Practice -- tChapter 10. A Streetcar Named (among Other Things) Proof -- tChapter 11. Mathematics and Narrative: An Aristotelian Perspective -- tChapter 12. Adventures of the Diagonal: Non-Euclidean Mathematics and Narrative -- tChapter 13. Formal Models in Narrative Analysis -- tChapter 14. Mathematics and Narrative: A Narratological Perspective -- tChapter 15. Tales of Contingency, Contingencies of Telling -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCircles Disturbed brings together important thinkers in mathematics, history, and philosophy to explore the relationship between mathematics and narrative. The book's title recalls the last words of the great Greek mathematician Archimedes before he was slain by a Roman soldier--"Don't disturb my circles"--words that seem to refer to two radically different concerns: that of the practical person living in the concrete world of reality, and that of the theoretician lost in a world of abstraction. Stories and theorems are, in a sense, the natural languages of these two worlds--stories representing the way we act and interact, and theorems giving us pure thought, distilled from the hustle and bustle of reality. Yet, though the voices of stories and theorems seem totally different, they share profound connections and similarities. A book unlike any other, Circles Disturbed delves into topics such as the way in which historical and biographical narratives shape our understanding of mathematics and mathematicians, the development of "myths of origins" in mathematics, the structure and importance of mathematical dreams, the role of storytelling in the formation of mathematical intuitions, the ways mathematics helps us organize the way we think about narrative structure, and much more. In addition to the editors, the contributors are Amir Alexander, David Corfield, Peter Galison, Timothy Gowers, Michael Harris, David Herman, Federica La Nave, G.E.R. Lloyd, Uri Margolin, Colin McLarty, Jan Christoph Meister, Arkady Plotnitsky, and Bernard Teissier.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCommunication in mathematics. 0aMathematicsxHistory. 0aMathematicsxLanguage. 7aMATHEMATICS / History & Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAlasdair MacIntyre.  aArchimedes.  aAristotle.  aBleak House.  aBorel sets.  aBourbaki.  aCarl Friedrich Gauss.  aDavid Hilbert.  aEmmy Noether.  aEnlightenment.  aG. E. R. Lloyd.  aGeorg Cantor.  aGreece.  aJean-Pierre Vernant.  aJohn Archibald Wheeler.  aK-ness.  aL'Al